<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
   <title> Try It Yourself </title>
   <style type="text/css">
      .div1 :not(p) {
         /* selects all elements which is not a <p> element */
         /* inside the <div class="div1"> element */
         color: red;
      }
         /* selects all elements which is not a <p> element */
         /* and don't have the class sorry inside the */
         /* <div class="div2"> element */
      .div2 p:not(.sorry) {
         color: red;
      }
   </style>
</head>
<body>
   <p> The <b>:not()</b> CSS pseudo-class represents elements that do not match a list of selectors. Since it prevents specific items from being selected, it is known as the negation pseudo-class. </p>
   
   <h3> Example: </h3>
   
   <p> On the example below all elements inside the &lt;div&gt; except the &lt;p&gt; element are selected. </p>
   <div class="div1">
      <h4> I am a heading element </h3>
      <span> I am a span element </span>
      <p> I am a paragraph element I don't get selected. </p>
   </div>
   
   <hr />
   
   <p> On the example below all elements inside the &lt;div&gt; except the &lt;p&gt; element with the class name <b>sorry</b> are selected. </p>
   <div class="div2">
      <p> I am a paragraph I DON'T have the <b>sorry</b> class name. </p>
      <p class="sorry"> I am a paragraph I have the <b>sorry</b> class name. </p>
      <p> I am a paragraph I DON'T have the <b>sorry</b> class name. </p>
   </div>
</body>
</html>